nodes.title: EnragedAntelope's Flux Upscale Workflow
widgets_values:
Flux Upscale Workflow by EnragedAntelope
https://civitai.com/user/EnragedAntelope
https://github.com/EnragedAntelope

What it does?
This workflow aims to get a clean Flux upscale with great detail, along with minimal or no streaking/artifacting that can sometimes occur with Flux. This took a lot of tweaking to get to a good place!
Very special thanks to Masslevel (https://civitai.com/user/masslevel) for helping so much along the way. 


How to use: 
1. Change latent size if desired, though I have heavily tested on the size I set here and can confirm great results. 
2. Set a prompt. Be sure to set the prompt switcher accordingly. 
3. Queue prompt. Really, that's it. Every other setting should be good to go.

You can easily jump to a group by clicking the arrows in the Fast Groups Bypasser (left of this message). 

You can choose to disable the Lora group if not using a lora, and the Add Grain group if you aren't interested in that. 

This takes about 160s (2m40s) on my 4090 from start to finish. It gives excellent quality so is worth the wait!. Don't forget that a good workflow is one piece of the puzzle, but a lot of details come from the right prompts.

Have fun!

Helpful links:
https://huggingface.co/marduk191/Flux.1_collection/tree/main for Flux all-in-one bundles.
https://openmodeldb.info/models/1x-Fatality-DeBlur for DeBlur "upscaler" (it doesn't upscale, maintains 1x image size - can sometimes help if you spot artifacts in the specific generation you're attempting). 
https://openmodeldb.info/models/4x-RealWebPhoto-v4-dat2 for the specific upscaler I've used here. You can search this site for other DAT2 upscalers to try if you work in other styles.

Add as many loras as your VRAM can handle using the Power Lora Loader, below. You can toggle on/off as necessary. The LoraLoaderVanilla node will output tags for your reference so you can utilize in future prompts.
